To make the $8$ triangles have the same area, the base must be divided into $8$ segments of length $1$ inch each.  Define points $A$, $B_0$, $B_1$, $B_2$, $B_3$, and $B_4$ as in the figure.  For $0\leq k\leq 3$, the perimeter $P(k)$ of triangle $A B_k B_{k+1}$ in inches is \[
P(k)=1+\sqrt{10^2+k^2}+\sqrt{10^2+(k+1)^2},
\]where each distance $A B_k$ is calculated by applying the Pythagorean theorem to right triangle $A B_0 B_k$.  Since $P(k)$ increases as $k$ increases, its largest value is $P(3)=1+\sqrt{100+3^2}+\sqrt{100+4^2}$, which to the nearest hundredth is $\boxed{22.21}$ inches.  [asy]
size(200);
defaultpen(linewidth(0.7)+fontsize(10));
draw((0,0)--(8,0));
for(int i = 0; i < 9; ++i){
draw((4,10)--(i,0));
if(i>=4)

label("$B_"+string(i-4)+"$",(i,0),S);
}
label("$A$",(4,10),N);
[/asy]

